t_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_3"][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Saving your template" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\n<p>You have three options for saving your template.</p><h4>Template (.ype) File</h4><p>You can save the template file (.ype) itself for editing later. Just navigate to File &gt; Save Template.</p><h4>PDF (for print)</h4><p>To download a high quality PDF of your template for printing, navigate to Download &gt; Save As PDF. In the "More Options" dropdown you can check whether you want crop marks or not.</p><h4>JPEG (for web)</h4><p>To download a jpeg image of your template for web use, navigate to Download &gt; Save As JPEG.</p>\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Locked Elements" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nYou might notice some elements are locked. This is to avoid accidentally moving them out of place. You can unlock an element at any time by selecting the element, click the dropdown arrow from the toolbar and select "unlock".\r\n\r\nYou can still make some changes to locked elements. Below is a list of some changes you can make to locked elements.\r\n\r\n<h4>Text</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Font style</li>\r\n	<li>Font size</li>\r\n	<li>Color</li>\r\n	<li>Edit text</li>\r\n	<li>Alignment</li>\r\n	<li>Opacity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Image Elements</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Color</li>\r\n	<li>Opacity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_3"][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Printing" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\n<p>This is the fun part. You''ve made the customizations to your template, now it''s time to print.</p><h4>Printing at home</h4><p>For templates 8 1/2" x 11" or smaller, printing at home is a perfect option. Here are some tips.</p><ul><li>Be sure the document prints at 100% (in the print settings). Sometimes "Scale to fit" will automatically be selected.</li><li>Test print one to make sure your print settings are correct before printing many copies.</li><li>The colors seen on your monitor may vary slightly when printed on paper. Test print one copy first and adjust the colors on the template is necessary.</li></ul><h4>Printing at a shop</h4><p>You also have the option of taking your PDF file to a print shop and getting it professionally printed. Any print shop should be able to handle the PDF file but some popular options are Staples®, Office Depot®, Office Max®, FedEx Kinkos®, and others. The PDF file is 300dpi which is the standard for professional printing.</p><h4>Paper</h4><p>Your intended use of the template will ultimately determine what kind of paper you print it on but in general we recommend printing on 80lb card stock. There are different weights of paper available to suit your needs.</p>\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]', 'Help', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '114-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-20 21:50:10', '2016-01-21 05:50:10', '', 114, 'http://youprintem.com/2016/01/20/114-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
