(302, 1, '2016-01-25 16:01:00', '2016-01-26 00:01:00', '[et_pb_section admin_label="section" transparent_background="off" allow_player_pause="off" inner_shadow="off" parallax="off" parallax_method="on" padding_mobile="off" make_fullwidth="off" use_custom_width="off" width_unit="on" make_equal="off" use_custom_gutter="off" gutter_width="3"][et_pb_row admin_label="row"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="center" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n<h1>Help</h1>\r\n[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row admin_label="row"][et_pb_column type="1_3"][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Opening your template" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nTo open your template file (.ype file), click the "Open Template" button in the popup when fist visiting the design application and select the template file you purchased and saved to your computer. Once selected, you can start customizing the template.\r\n\r\nPlease note, trying to open the .ype file on your computer will not do anything. It must be loaded into our design application to work.\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Trimming" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nCutting your template out is fairly straight forward, however there are a few different methods to do it – some of which are easier than others.\r\n<h4>Scissors</h4>\r\nScissors can be used to trim the template but keep in mind you''ll need a steady hand. It''s not really the preferred option.\r\n<h4>Exacto knife and straight edge</h4>\r\nUsing an exacto knife and straight edge is a perfect way to get great results when trimming your template. Be sure to put something underneath so you don''t ruin the table below.\r\n<h4>Paper trimmer</h4>\r\nUsing a paper trimmer is the quickest option for cutting your templates to size and you can easily get accurate results every time. This method is ideal if you already have one, or if you have a lot of templates to trim.\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_3"][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Saving your template" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nYou have three options for saving your template.\r\n<h4>Template (.ype) File</h4>\r\nYou can save the template file (.ype) itself for editing later. Just navigate to File &gt; Save Template.\r\n<h4>PDF (for print)</h4>\r\nTo download a high quality PDF of your template for printing, navigate to Download &gt; Save As PDF. In the "More Options" dropdown you can check whether you want crop marks or not.\r\n<h4>JPEG (for web)</h4>\r\nTo download a jpeg image of your template for web use, navigate to Download &gt; Save As JPEG.\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Locked Elements" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nYou might notice some elements are locked. This is to avoid accidentally moving them out of place. You can unlock an element at any time by selecting the element, click the dropdown arrow from the toolbar and select "unlock".\r\n\r\nYou can still make some changes to locked elements. Below is a list of some changes you can make to locked elements.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h4>Text</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Font style</li>\r\n	<li>Font size</li>\r\n	<li>Color</li>\r\n	<li>Edit text</li>\r\n	<li>Alignment</li>\r\n	<li>Opacity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Image Elements</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Color</li>\r\n	<li>Opacity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_3"][et_pb_toggle admin_label="Toggle" title="Printing" open="off" title_font_size="16" body_font_size="14" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]\r\n\r\nThis is the fun part. You''ve made the customizations to your template, now it''s time to print.\r\n<h4>Printing at home</h4>\r\nFor templates 8 1/2" x 11" or smaller, printing at home is a perfect option. Here are some tips.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Be sure the document prints at 100% (in the print settings). Sometimes "Scale to fit" will automatically be selected.</li>\r\n	<li>Test print one to make sure your print settings are correct before printing many copies.</li>\r\n	<li>The colors seen on your monitor may vary slightly when printed on paper. Test print one copy first and adjust the colors on the template is necessary.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Printing at a shop</h4>\r\nYou also have the option of taking your PDF file to a print shop and getting it professionally printed. Any print shop should be able to handle the PDF file but some popular options are Staples®, Office Depot®, Office Max®, FedEx Kinkos®, and others. The PDF file is 300dpi which is the standard for professional printing.\r\n<h4>Paper</h4>\r\nYour intended use of the template will ultimately determine what kind of paper you print it on but in general we recommend printing on 80lb card stock. There are different weights of paper available to suit your needs.\r\n\r\n[/et_pb_toggle][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]', 'Help', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '114-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-25 16:01:00', '2016-01-26 00:01:00', '', 114, 'http://youprintem.com/2016/01/25/114-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
